I took a short break recently and looked into web development, specifically developing with WebAssembly, Rust, and Leptos. I'm not too experienced with web development so it will take the most time to develop. So far, I've been researching the best way to make the API client for the frontend which I have almost fully developed in a separate open-sourced project inspired by an article: Designing Rust bindings for REST APIs ⋅ Plume (benboeckel.net). Today, I have committed an early incomplete version to the NEA project which I will replace later with the open-sourced version.

Today, I decided to make some adjustments to the backend to optimise it. The current system sends the short description and the long description which is not optimal as the client could look those up locally instead. This could cause some issues if there was an outdated client, but these cases can be handled by telling the user to update or display a generic message.

Furthermore, while JSON is good for testing, the responses can be optimised further via Protocol Buffers. After successfully implementing it, my content length has decreased to 4 bytes for majority of endpoints that do not provide any additional data.

The POST v1/user/register endpoint:


Currently, the payload is sent as JSON but I will convert it to Protocol Buffers in the future.

When converting to protobufs, I had to create a derive macro to help me create the boilerplate that converts the protobuf-converted Rust structs to a "cleaner" version of the same struct which I can expand upon (such as adding the validation for payloads).

Unfortunately, Postman does not support Protocol Buffer endpoints (but they do support gRPC) so I had to switch to a similar application: Protoman.

After successfully changing entirely to protobufs, I plan to create the frontend's "backend" which would manage the state and finally create the design and frontend itself.

Here is some statistics explaining the advantages of protobuf vs JSON (Beating JSON performance with Protobuf (auth0.com)) where protobuf wins consistantly.
